|BKB***************************************************************************
                        |CKBArea Building Overview
|BKB***************************************************************************

|GKOAreas are where players go to kill stuff, do quests etc. Creating an area
is as much an artistic endeavour as it is a technical one, but the process
should not be a haphazard and random. Of course builders can us any process
they want to get the job done, but if they use a shitty process, it's their
own damned fault, and will get approximately 0 sympathy from me. The
procedure and guidelines listed here is a good starting point for beginning
builders.


|BKB***************************************************************************
                              |CKBPlanning
|BKB***************************************************************************

|GKOBefore writing a single line of code, the area should be planned out.
First, pick a theme for the area - a one line description of what the whole
area is about. For example:
 
    |YKOEves and vikings in a perpetual war.
    Ruined temple to Athena in some swamps.
    Settlement of desert dwarves.
    Dwarven mines that produce metals in Mitra's name.
    
|GKOKeep in mind that the theme for Darkwind is fantasy.  Your area must fit
into this theme to be added to the game.  No cyber realms or modern day
areas will be considered. Next, flesh out the area with some rough details,
again before coding. For example:

    |YKOArea in the underworld with mineral mines and an attached mining
    town full of dwarves. Dwarves are mining for metals which are used
    to make weapons for Mitra's holy armies. Monster levels are 10-25
    with a few special BS monsters. Are is good/lawful aligned.
    Astute players will be able to custom make one special exceptional
    weapon for their own use. Total of about 50 rooms.

|GKONext, make a map of the area. The map can be on paper, but a text file is
better since you can then include it with your area as supporting
documentation. Fill in the map with notes on where mobs are, treasures are,
special questy things etc. Lay out the entire area before writing a single
line of code.


|BKB***************************************************************************
                              |CKBCoding
|BKB***************************************************************************

|GKOFirst, lay out your directory structure and headers. Since you've planned
out what will exist, you can create a directory for the area, and
subdirectories for things like rooms, monsters etc. Set up a header file
that contains #defines to the appropriate directory paths. At no time
should a path be hardcoded into the action objects in your area.

Next lay down the topology. Basically put down all the rooms and
connections (name the rooms correctly right off the bad) without setting up
any properties etc. You want to be able to walk around the area even if
there's nothing there yet. Once the rooms are there, fill them in with all
the setting they need and the descs, but NOT the objects they contain like
loot and monsters. Also, don't put in any special code yet - just set up
the basic rooms. What you have now is a fully laid out, deserted area.

The next step is to populate the area with restocking items (i.e. mobs and
room contents that respawn). The difficulty here is that mobs carry items
and you haven't made those yet. So now, go and make all the items that
exist, but do them in their most basic forms - no add_actions or special
stuff outside the reset() function. Then make all the mobs, and make sure
they load up the required items. Finally add the restocking items to each
of the rooms as appropriate. Now you have a basic, stocked area, but
lacking features like add_actions, questy things etc. This area should
stand on its own already as a basic, killing area.

Now add all the special stuff to make your quests and whatnot work. In the
course of this, you may have to alter descs etc. to give out hints, and do
other funky stuff. Since you've already filled in the basics of the area
you should be able to concentrate on just the special code.

The end. Have your mentor check it over, then submit it for review.


|BKB***************************************************************************
                           |CKBSome Dos and Don'ts
|BKB*************************************************************************

|RKBDo not make deadly traps without hints

    |YKOA player must never die because there was some unforseeable
    danger in the next room. Of course if there are signs and they
    ignore them (giant, dragon footprints leading into a cave) it's
    their own damned fault...
    
|RKBDon't make things too good (or bad)

    |YKOThere's a balance between challenge and reward. If your area leans
    too far one way or the other, it's bad. High challenge should net
    high rewards and vice versa. Remember that the purpose of the game
    is for it to be fun and enjoyable both for players and for wizards 
    - not to have all players converge on your castle just to get that
    wc 30 sword.
    
|RKBDon't submit an area for review that you KNOW has problems

    |YKOReviews are for VERIFYING that an area is OK. It's not a bug-fixing
    step. 
    
|RKBDon't make a HUGE area and submit it all at once

    |YKOBreak it up into smaller, more manageable chunks. It's better that
    way for both the builder and the reviewer. Each chunk doesn't have
    to go into play piece by piece - they can get approved and wait for
    the whole thing to be done.
    
